<p class=""><h2>Key Challenges in the Prebiotics for Infant Formula Market</h2><ul>    <li>        <strong>Regulatory Compliance:</strong> Navigating the complex regulatory landscape poses a significant challenge. Manufacturers must comply with stringent safety and labeling requirements, which can be resource-intensive and may vary by region.    </li>    <li>        <strong>High Production Costs:</strong> The production of prebiotics, particularly high-quality variants, involves considerable investment in R&D and raw materials. This can lead to higher costs for manufacturers, impacting pricing strategies and profit margins.    </li>    <li>        <strong>Limited Consumer Awareness:</strong> Despite growing awareness of probiotics, many consumers still lack understanding of prebiotics and their benefits. This knowledge gap can hinder market growth as parents may be reluctant to choose formulas fortified with prebiotics.    </li>    <li>        <strong>Ingredient Sourcing:</strong> Securing a consistent supply of natural and high-quality prebiotic ingredients can be challenging, especially with fluctuating agricultural conditions and climate impacts affecting availability.    </li>    <li>        <strong>Competition with Other Supplements:</strong> The infant formula market is crowded with various nutritional supplements and additives. The presence of competitive products can dilute the market share for prebiotic-enhanced formulas.    </li></ul><h2>Potential Growth Opportunities</h2><ul>    <li>        <strong>Increasing Demand for Functional Foods:</strong> As awareness of gut health expands, so does the demand for functional foods, including infant formulas fortified with prebiotics. This trend presents opportunities for product innovation and differentiation.    </li>    <li>        <strong>Rising Health Consciousness Among Parents:</strong> Parents are increasingly focused on nutrition and wellness, driving interest in prebiotic infant formulas. Marketing campaig